    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You should absolutely normalize your features because algorithms like neural networks and gradient-based optimizers are highly sensitive to the scale of input data. If one feature has a range of 0-1 and another spans 1000-5000, the optimizer will struggle to find the optimal weights, leading to very slow convergence, unstable training, or even complete failure. This is because the gradients will be dominated by the larger values, causing the model to ignore the smaller, yet equally important, features.\n\nThink of it like trying to balance a scale where one side has a feather and the other has a boulder; the boulder completely overwhelms the system, preventing it from detecting the weight of the feather. In machine learning, this imbalance causes the loss landscape to become distorted, making it difficult for the model to learn effective patterns.\n\nNormalization ensures that all features contribute equally to the learning process, allowing the model to train much faster and reach a better solution. It's not just about making numbers look pretty; it's a fundamental requirement for the mathematical stability of most modern models. Without it, you're essentially asking your model to learn while wearing heavy boots, which is why you'll see significantly better performance and efficiency once you standard",
